</section>

  <section class=3D"nsw-section nsw-section--half-padding">
  <div class=3D"nsw-container">
   =20
  <div class=3D"nsw-content-block">
    <div class=3D"nsw-content-block__content">
          <h2 class=3D"nsw-p-y-sm" id=3D"-industrial-salinity-">
        Industrial salinity
      <a href=3D"https://www.environment.nsw.gov.au/topics/land-and-soil/so=
il-degradation/salinity/types-and-prevention#-industrial-salinity-" class=
=3D"anchor sr-only" tabindex=3D"-1">Industrial salinity</a></h2>
                  <div class=3D"nsw-content-block__copy">  <p>Many industri=
al processes have the potential to increase salinity levels in rivers. Exam=
ples are:</p><ul><li>saline water from mines (working and abandoned) from g=
roundwater seepage and from rainwater coming into contact with mine working=
s or spoil</li><li>discharged cooling water from coal-fired power stations =
that has been partly evaporated, concentrating the salt content</li><li>eff=
luent being discharged.</li></ul>
</div>
              </div>
</div>
  </div>
</section>

  <section class=3D"nsw-section nsw-section--half-padding">
  <div class=3D"nsw-container">
   =20
  <div class=3D"nsw-content-block">
    <div class=3D"nsw-content-block__content">
          <h2 class=3D"nsw-p-y-sm" id=3D"-river-salinity-">
        River salinity
      <a href=3D"https://www.environment.nsw.gov.au/topics/land-and-soil/so=
il-degradation/salinity/types-and-prevention#-river-salinity-" class=3D"anc=
hor sr-only" tabindex=3D"-1">River salinity</a></h2>
                  <div class=3D"nsw-content-block__copy">  <p>As salty wate=
r from areas affected by dryland, irrigation and urban salinity flows into =
creeks and rivers, the concentration (electrical conductivity or EC) and vo=
lume (load) of salt increases. Over time, as salinity within catchments wor=
sens, the quality of river water declines.</p><p>Many factors influence ele=
ctrical conductivity levels but salt load is driven by the volume of water =
flow.</p><p>Much of New South Wales falls within the Murray-Darling Basin. =
The Murray-Darling Basin Authority has developed the strategy <a href=3D"ht=
tps://www.mdba.gov.au/publications-and-data/publications/basin-salinity-man=
agement-2030-strategies-and-reports" class=3D"ext" data-extlink=3D"" rel=3D=
"noreferrer">Basin salinity management 2030<svg focusable=3D"false" width=
=3D"1em" height=3D"1em" class=3D"ext" data-extlink-placement=3D"append" ari=
a-label=3D"(link is external)" viewBox=3D"0 0 80 40" role=3D"img" aria-hidd=
en=3D"false"><title>(link is external)</title><path d=3D"M48 26c-1.1 0-2 0.=
9-2 2v26H10V18h26c1.1 0 2-0.9 2-2s-0.9-2-2-2H8c-1.1 0-2 0.9-2 2v40c0 1.1 0.=
9 2 2 2h40c1.1 0 2-0.9 2-2V28C50 26.9 49.1 26 48 26z"></path><path d=3D"M56=
 6H44c-1.1 0-2 0.9-2 2s0.9 2 2 2h7.2L30.6 30.6c-0.8 0.8-0.8 2 0 2.8C31 33.8=
 31.5 34 32 34s1-0.2 1.4-0.6L54 12.8V20c0 1.1 0.9 2 2 2s2-0.9 2-2V8C58 6.9 =
57.1 6 56 6z"></path></svg></a> to deliver coordinated salinity management =
of land and waterways within the basin.</p>
</div>
              </div>
</div>
  </div>
</section>

  <section class=3D"nsw-section component--multi-column-listing--wrapper ns=
w-section--half-padding">
  <div class=3D"component component--multi-column-listing paragraph nsw-con=
tainer paragraph--type--multi-column-listing paragraph--view-mode--default"=
